    id: 1154,
    header: "MY SOUL'S DESIRE",
    question: "Chapter 4 suggests that a soul comes to the mortal world to fulfill its desires. How do I get to know my soul's desires. How do I differentiate it from my worldly desires? Does it suggests that to attain Moksha, fulfilling my soul's desires are more important than my devotion to the Lord?",
    answer: "Divine Soul,\n\nImagine a bonded labor. A capitalist gives him loan and applies so much interest that the labor is not able to pay even the interest. He keeps working for the capitalist all his life. Then his child also works under capitalist. The child has not taken the loan but he was told that he owes money to capitalist. So he also keeps working till death for the capitalist, Then his child is born in such environment that he thinks that life is all about working for the capitalist till death. He even doesn't bother to ask the capitalist as to how much money he owes him.\n\nSame is the case with soul. It comes here for a single desire but it forgets its true identity in the world. The soul think that it is a body not a soul.\n\nYou don't need to know what your desires are. You need to know who you are.\n\nHow does devotion come into picture? Devotion is an activity. What originates the activity? How did you start the devotion. You started because of a desire --- may be a desire to be free from all desires, or a desire to get rid of worldly problems. Desire is a deep term. Do not equate it with the \"desire\" word which we use in day to day life.\n\nBlessings"
