    header: "QUESTION REGARDING EARTHWORM.",
    question: "When I was child, an iron bucket fell on an earthworm by mistake. Due to this earthworm was half inside the base and half outside. It splitted in two parts and both the parts moved on separately.\nIf we believe on single body single soul then this appears contradictory. But after reading these chapters what I concluded is we are surrounded with so many souls. And when the earthworm splits, one soul enters one of the part and hence both parts are alive.\n\nSo is this interpretation correct or not???",
    answer: "Divine Soul,\n\nIf something is \"moving\", \"and seem to have life in it\", it does not mean that it has a soul.\n\nBut what you tried to interpret is not absurd. You are very close to knowing something very deep. If you continue with this line of thought, you will find the truth.\n\nSuggestion : separate \"instrument\" and \"soul\". A soul uses an \"instrument\" to experience the universe. Anything you can imagine, or anything you can see can serve as an instrument for a soul. Even a stone can be an instrument for a soul. Both parts of the earthworm can serve as instruments for two souls.\n\nWhen you explore more, you will find that souls are infinite in number. But do not conclude there. Ask another question, \"The soul who tends to conclude that souls are infinite, does that soul have the authority to conclude so? Isn't that soul just one out of the infinite souls.\"\n\nThis way, when you keep exploring, without concluding anything, you will taste the supreme truth.\n\nBlessings"
