    question: "Jai Shri Krishna\n\nAs per what I understood after reading 11 chapters, I have a few questions. Maybe they will be answered in other chapters. Before I forget, here are my questions:\n\n1. Our karma is based on our actions, but when we say that the surrahs and assurahs influence our soul and it is not our soul that has done the deed, so why is that we have to balance our karma, which is not really ours anyways. I mean our soul is using the body as an instrument, similarly the surrahs and assurahs are doing the same thus leading to our karma. (I am not sure if I am being articulate enough). So why is the soul responsible for the actions of assurahs and surrahs. Is it because our souls allowed them to enter. If that is the case then, please enlighten us on how we can avoid this from happening.\n\n2. Also please enlighten me if I understood this clearly: a soul dissolves in muktisagar after achieving moksha and a new soul takes birth. So this new soul will have to go through the same process till it reaches moksha? This means there are infinite number of souls as there could be many different combinations that could arise from muktisagar. (From Chapter 4)\n\n3. Also, what is the basis of desire if a soul just came from muktisagar (where all desires were fulfilled).\n\n4. Is there any relationship between 7 strings of time and the 7 chakras of body. Also, how does one gain more than 7 strings of time like the noble woman, who later became Urmi. What are the benefits of having more than 7 strings of time, unless one has to donate them to save a life?\n\n5. Why does Shukracharya have animosity toward Lord Vishnu? (Chapter 8)\n\nThank you to everyone behind this project, for making it understandable and articulate. Also Thank you to the Mathangs for sharing this supreme knowledge. The maanav lok is truly blessed to have Lord Hanuman to guide our souls to moksha.\n\nThank you all.\nJai Sia Ram.",
